ce:section.ce:para:
ZnO has superior photocatalytic properties under light irradiation derived from their semiconductor structure and surface defects, which results in the production of reactive oxygen species (ROS), including hydroxyl radicals (OH•), singlet oxygen (1O2), superoxide anions (O2 
                        •−), and hydrogen peroxide (H2O2). These radicals' species play essential roles in antimicrobial activity through oxidative damage to DNA and the membrane of microbes. ZnO can also generate Zn+2 ions that are essential in interfering with bacterial growth [74]. CNDs materials have a rich surface of hydroxyl (OH) and carboxyl groups (COOH), indicating a massive release of free radicals and ROS based on light intensity. These are known to destroy various microorganisms' cell components, such as DNA, lipids, and proteins leading to cell death [46], Therefore, the hybrid combination can lead to a high ROS synergistic effect mechanism with a noticeable increment of glutathione deficiency percentage. Hybrid was the highest with stronger noticeable signals of reactive oxygen and hydroxyl radicals, indicating that the photocatalytic degradation process of hybrid enhanced by visible light region with additional electronic transitions in the same orbits is more prone to occur. This could be ascribed to the establishment of an intermediate energy level above the valence band of ZnO and a decrease in the band gap to 2.8 eV [69]. (See the scheme in Fig. 10
                        ).
